vectorData.altText: 23. Which spinal levels contribute to the sacral plexus? Choose all that apply.

That's right! The sacral plexus contain ventral rami from L4 to S4 spinal levels. It forms in the pelvis, and together with the lumbar plexus, give rise to peripheral nerves that innervate the lower limb, abdominal wall and perineum.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Nerves of the lower limb serve three broad purposes: i) they control skeletal muscles (somatic motor fibres) so as to allow us to walk or ride a bike, for instance, i) they provide sensory feedback to the CNS (somatic sensory fibres) which, in turn, informs our movements, and iii) they control vascular

resistance and sweat glands, and therefore the distribution of blood to skeletal muscle and skin as well as body temperature (sympathetic postganglionic fibres).
The peripheral nerves of the lower limb are derived from the lumbar and sacral plexuses, which are formed from the ventral rami of lumbar and sacral spinal nerves. The lumbar plexus (L1-L4) forms in the posterior abdominal wall, and the sacral plexus (L4-S4) forms in the pelvis. They give rise to the peripheral nerves that innervate the lower limb, as well as those that innervate the abdominal wall and perineum.
The blood supply to the lower limb is derived from the external iliac artery, which passes from the false pelvis, under the inguinal ligament, to become the femoral artery. Venous blood ultimately drains away from the lower limb via the femoral vein, which passes under the inguinal ligament to become the external iliac vein in the false pelvis.
